sshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Philiphaugh, Scottish Borders, Scotland":"Scottish Borders, Scotland, United Kingdom","Traquair, Peebles-shire, Scotland":"Traquair, Peeblesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Falahill, Midlothian, Scotland":"Falahill, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Murray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Moray in northeastern Scotland, which derives from Celtic <i>mori-</i> ‘sea’ + <i>treb-</i> ‘settlement’. The founder of the Scottish house of Murray was a Fleming named Freskin who was granted Strathbrock in West Lothian and Duffus in Moray by David I. The family took its name from the region in the late 12th century.","Irish and Scottish: shortened form of   McMurray  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Muireadhaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Muireadhach</i>’ a personal name meaning ‘mariner’. Occasionally it may be a shortened form of   McMurray  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Murri","meanings":["Probably Scottish: variant of   Murray  ."]},{"name":"Murry","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: variant of   Murray  ."]},{"name":"Murrah","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Scottish   Murray  ."]},{"name":"Murie","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Michel.","Scottish: habitational name from Murie in Errol (Perthshire).","Scottish and Irish: variant of   Murray  ."]},{"name":"Merhi","meanings":["Arabic (mainly Lebanon and Syria): from a variant of the personal name <i>Mirhi</i> of unknown meaning. Bearers of this surname are both Muslims and Christians. Compare   Murray   5."]},{"name":"Murrey","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Murray  ."]},{"name":"McMurray","meanings":["Irish (northern) and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Muireadhaigh</b> or <b>Mac Muireadhaich</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Muireadhach</i> ‘seafarer’ (see   Murdoch  ). Compare   McCurry   1."]},{"name":"Murra","meanings":["Italian (Sicily): topographic name from Sicilian <i>murra</i> ‘large rock, mass of rocks’ or a habitational name from a place called with this word.","East Frisian: unexplained.","Albanian: nickname from <i>murrë</i> (definite form <i>murra</i>) ‘dark gray cow’."]},{"name":"Murrie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Murray  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Murray was born in 1442, in Falahill, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Patrick Murray of Dollerie and Ochtertyre, was 20 and her mother, Catharina Balfour, was 17. She died on 11 August 1512, in Traquair, Peeblesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 70, and was buried in Peeblesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1442–11 August 1512":"1442–11. august 1512","1442–1512":"1442–1512","1422–1476":"1422–1476","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","1469":"1469","1425":"1425","1512":"1512","1422":"1422","1476":"1476","1442":"1442","11 August 1512":"11. august 1512","Peebles-shire, Scotland":"Peeblesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Philiphaugh, Scottish Borders, Scotland":"Scottish Borders, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Traquair, Peebles-shire, Scotland":"Traquair, Peeblesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Falahill, Midlothian, Scotland":"Falahill, Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1442–11 August 1512":"1442–11. elokuuta 1512","1442–1512":"1442–1512","1422–1476":"1422–1476","1425–Female":"1425–Kuollut","1469":"1469","1425":"1425","1512":"1512","1422":"1422","1476":"1476","1442":"1442","11 August 1512":"11. elokuuta 1512","Peebles-shire, Scotland":"Peeblesshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Philiphaugh, Scottish Borders, Scotland":"Scottish Borders, Skotlanti,